<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C62FF89FF71FAF3FE64F3AD" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF71FAF3FDB0F3DD" blockId="4.[166,606,1391,1418]" box="[166,606,1391,1418]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
<heading id="6F6881EC6C62FF89FF71FAF3FDB0F3DD" box="[166,606,1391,1418]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="F39F4D036C62FF89FF71FAF3FDB0F3DD" authority="Boisduval, 1840" authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1840" box="[166,606,1391,1418]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cucullia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xeranthemi">
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C62FF89FF71FAF3FE70F3DD" bold="true" box="[166,414,1391,1418]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">Cucullia xeranthemi</emphasis>
Boisduval, 1840
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFA03FE64F3AD" blockId="4.[166,1225,1439,1850]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FDADFA03FD28F3ED" box="[634,710,1439,1466]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 21</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="F3679B656C62FF89FCFBFA03FC54F3ED" box="[812,954,1439,1466]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.499999999999999" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" unit="mm" value="0.6499999999999999" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.7 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="F3679B656C62FF89FBE1FA03FB7EF3ED" box="[1078,1168,1439,1466]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
(n = = 3). Fresh egg white. As egg develops, it becomes pale pink. Before caterpillar emergence egg becoming grey.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C62FF87FF0CFA63FD9EF69D" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="4" pageNumber="357" type="description">
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFA63FDCEF0AD" blockId="4.[166,1225,1439,1850]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surfaces. Micropylar area clearly expressed, represented by rosette and 3 rows short and broad cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FC9EF983FC76F06D" box="[841,920,1567,1594]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Rosette and cells of first series have floors with clearly expressed long and narrow ledges (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FC64F9A3FBECF00D" box="[947,1026,1599,1626]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Micropylar rosette elevated with 6–10 cells and 4 micropylar opening 
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C62FF89FCEEF9C3FCAAF02E" bold="true" box="[825,836,1631,1657]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">s</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FC83F9C3FC4CF02D" box="[852,930,1631,1658]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 24</figureCitation>
). There are 10–13 of 24– 25 clearly expressed longitudinal ridges radiate from tertiary cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FC6CF9E3FBE6F0CD" box="[955,1032,1663,1690]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Longest ridges with high comb especially in anterior portions (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FD0AF903FCC5F0ED" box="[733,811,1695,1722]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Transverse walls less distinct and narrow than ridges. Aeropyles weakly expressed at walls junctions. The entire surface looks like of shallow network (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FE11F943FDFDF0AD" box="[454,531,1759,1786]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CF963FEBBF16D" blockId="4.[166,1225,1439,1850]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
Shape of gnawed holes in eggs. Caterpillar nibbles out large oval opening at lateral part of egg (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FF2CF883FEA6F16D" box="[251,328,1823,1850]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[170,203,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[170,1228,194,1690]" captionTargetId="figure-11@5.[170,1228,194,1692]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Metoponiinae: 19, 20 — Tyta luctuosa; eggs of Cuculliinae: 21–24 — Cucullia xeranthemi. Scale bars: 21 — 100 µm; 19, 20, 22, 23 — 10 µm; 24 — 1.0 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453292/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
